 Port Elizabeth - Port Elizabeth K9 unit members arrested four alleged abalone poachers on Monday afternoon after they received a call for assistance from the Dark Water Ops -  also called the anti- abalone poaching unit. "It is alleged that at about 12:00 on Monday, the anti- poaching unit observed suspicious activity at Noordhoek beach in Marine Drive," described police spokesperson, Col Priscilla Naidu. "The K9 unit members were contacted for assistance." She said that a diver retrieved two large bags containing fresh abalone from the water -  about 481 units. "The estimated street value of the abalone is over R1 million," Col Naidu said. "Diving equipment and a silver grey Citroen belonging to the suspects was also confiscated." She added that the suspects, aged between 32 and 51 years old, were detained on a charge of illegal possession of abalone. "They are expected to appear in the Port Elizabeth Magistrate's on Tuesday." Follow more RNEWS articles, subscribe to our YouTube channel and for breaking news LIKE us on Facebook. For news on the Western Cape click here. For great savings on life’s little pleasures visit Bargain Buys!  Know somebody who is getting married, Wedding and Function can assist.  Have kids, then you need to visit Kids Connection. Enjoy food and travel, then visit Home Food and Travel. Need assistance with an online presence, visit Agency One. 